<td colspan="9">An atmospheric test of the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon_2" title="SpaceX Dragon 2">Dragon 2</a> abort system after <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Max_Q" title="Max Q">Max Q</a>. The capsule fired its <a href="/wiki/SuperDraco" title="SuperDraco">SuperDraco</a> engines, reached an apogee of 40km (25mi), deployed parachutes, and <a href="/wiki/Splashdown" title="Splashdown">splashed down</a> in the ocean 31km (19mi) downrange from the launch site. The test was previously slated to be accomplished with the <a href="/wiki/Crew_Dragon_Demo-1" title="Crew Dragon Demo-1">Crew Dragon Demo-1</a> capsule;<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-nsf-20170811_24-0"><a href="#cite_note-nsf-20170811-24">[18]</a></sup> but that test article exploded during a ground test of SuperDraco engines on 20 April 2019.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-:11_25-0"><a href="#cite_note-:11-25">[19]</a></sup> The abort test used the capsule originally intended for the first crewed flight.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sfn_crewdragon_may19_26-0"><a href="#cite_note-sfn_crewdragon_may19-26">[20]</a></sup> As expected, the booster was destroyed by aerodynamic forces after the capsule aborted.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-27"><a href="#cite_note-27">[21]</a></sup> First flight of a Falcon 9 with only one functional stage  the second stage had a <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Mass_simulator" title="Mass simulator">mass simulator</a> in place of its engine.

<tr>
<td colspan="9">Payload manufacturing contract awarded January 2012,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gps_34_manufacturing_59-0"><a href="#cite_note-gps_34_manufacturing-59">[53]</a></sup> fully assembled in August 2017,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gpsworld_20171127_60-0"><a href="#cite_note-gpsworld_20171127-60">[54]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gleckel-2017-11_61-0"><a href="#cite_note-gleckel-2017-11-61">[55]</a></sup> and completed thermal vacuum testing in June 2018.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-gps_status_20180926_62-0"><a href="#cite_note-gps_status_20180926-62">[56]</a></sup> Launch contract was awarded initially for US$96.5 million,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-63"><a href="#cite_note-63">[57]</a></sup> but later, this was discounted in exchange for allowing to launch configuration enabling booster recovery.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-64"><a href="#cite_note-64">[58]</a></sup> The vehicle nicknamed <i>Columbus</i> was transported to Florida in February 2020,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-65"><a href="#cite_note-65">[59]</a></sup> but launch was delayed by the customer from April 2020 due to the <a href="/wiki/COVID-19" title="COVID-19">COVID-19</a> pandemic.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sn20200407_66-0"><a href="#cite_note-sn20200407-66">[60]</a></sup> The launch was dedicated to the memory of the recently deceased, late commander of the <a href="/wiki/21st_Space_Wing" title="21st Space Wing">21st Space Wing</a>, Colonel Thomas G. Falzarano,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sn20200630_67-0"><a href="#cite_note-sn20200630-67">[61]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-s&amp;s20200513_68-0"><a href="#cite_note-s&amp;s20200513-68">[62]</a></sup> and after launch, in October 2020, the nickname was changed to that of the Arctic explorer <a href="/wiki/Matthew_Henson" title="Matthew Henson">Matthew Henson</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-GPS_69-0"><a href="#cite_note-GPS-69">[63]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-sn-20160427_70-0"><a href="#cite_note-sn-20160427-70">[64]</a></sup> The second stage featured a gray band to allow more heat to be absorbed during the longer coasting period,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-71"><a href="#cite_note-71">[65]</a></sup> while both fairings were recovered out of the water without attempting a catch in the net.

<td colspan="9">At 5-6 tonnes, the satellite formerly known as <i>K-Milsat-1</i> is South Korea's first dedicated military satellite. Contracted by South Korea's <a href="/wiki/Defense_Acquisition_Program_Administration" title="Defense Acquisition Program Administration">Defense Acquisition Program Administration</a> in 2014.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-74"><a href="#cite_note-74">[68]</a></sup> 57th successful recovery of a Falcon 9 first stage. For the first time both fairing halves were also successfully caught by <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Ms._Tree_(ship)" title="Ms. Tree (ship)">fairing catching ships</a>.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-75"><a href="#cite_note-75">[69]</a></sup> This launch featured a booster reflight within 51 days, a new record turnaround time for a Falcon booster.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-76"><a href="#cite_note-76">[70]</a></sup> It was the same booster that launched the <a href="/wiki/Crew_Dragon_Demo-2" title="Crew Dragon Demo-2">Crew Dragon Demo-2</a> spacecraft on 30 May 2020.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-SFN20200720_72-1"><a href="#cite_note-SFN20200720-72">[66]</a></sup> The satellite was delivered to a <a class="mw-redirect" href="/wiki/Super-synchronous_transfer_orbit" title="Super-synchronous transfer orbit">super-synchronous transfer orbit</a> of 211km 45,454km (131mi 28,244mi), while both fairing halves were caught in the catch nets of the supports ships.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-77"><a href="#cite_note-77">[71]</a></sup>

<td colspan="9">First crew rotation of the commercial crew program, following the return in August of the crewed test flight mission <a href="/wiki/Crew_Dragon_Demo-2" title="Crew Dragon Demo-2">Crew Demo 2</a>. Originally designated "USCV-1" by NASA. Carried astronauts <a href="/wiki/Victor_J._Glover" title="Victor J. Glover">Victor Glover</a>, <a href="/wiki/Michael_S._Hopkins" title="Michael S. Hopkins">Mike Hopkins</a>, <a href="/wiki/Shannon_Walker" title="Shannon Walker">Shannon Walker</a> and <a href="/wiki/Soichi_Noguchi" title="Soichi Noguchi">Soichi Noguchi</a>, for a 6-month stay aboard the ISS, during which the <a href="/wiki/Boeing_Starliner" title="Boeing Starliner">Boeing Starliner</a> <a href="/wiki/Boeing_Orbital_Flight_Test" title="Boeing Orbital Flight Test">OFT</a> flight launched but was unable to dock as expected.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-112"><a href="#cite_note-112">[106]</a></sup> The first flight of the crew program was initially expected to launch in 2017,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-113"><a href="#cite_note-113">[107]</a></sup><sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-scientificamerican-2_114-0"><a href="#cite_note-scientificamerican-2-114">[108]</a></sup> and finished final certifications in November 2020.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-115"><a href="#cite_note-115">[109]</a></sup>

<tr>
<td colspan="9">Launched the largest, high-power broadcasting satellite for SiriusXM's <a href="/wiki/Digital_audio_radio_service" title="Digital audio radio service">digital audio radio service</a> (DARS). SXM-7 was built by <a href="/wiki/Maxar_Technologies" title="Maxar Technologies">Maxar Technologies</a>; intended to operate in the <a href="/wiki/S_band" title="S band">S-band</a> spectrum, it will replace the SXM-3 satellite. The satellite will deliver the highest power density of any commercial satellite on-orbit,<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-127"><a href="#cite_note-127">[121]</a></sup> generate more than 20kW of power, and have a large unfoldable antenna reflector, which enables broadcast to radios without the need for large dish-type antennas on the ground. Due to the heavy weight, the payload was injected into a sub-synchronous orbit of 224km 19,411km (139mi 12,061mi) and the satellite itself will transfer to full GTO.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-128"><a href="#cite_note-128">[122]</a></sup> It was the first time a commercial primary payload flew on a booster which had been flown more than 4 times before.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-auto3_129-0"><a href="#cite_note-auto3-129">[123]</a></sup> First dedicated customer launch where the fairings were previously used.<sup class="reference" id="cite_ref-130"><a href="#cite_note-130">[124]</a></sup>
</td></tr>

"""
Retrieve the columns on from th with class scope

"""
column_names = []

for column in My_table.findAll('th',{"scope":"col"}):
    
    
    column_names.append(column.get_text())

for i,n in enumerate(column_names):
    column_names[i] = n.strip()

print(column_names);

['Flight No.', 'Date andtime (UTC)', 'Version,booster[b]', 'Launchsite', 'Payload[c]', 'Payload mass', 'Orbit', 'Customer', 'Launchoutcome', 'Boosterlanding']
In [6]:
"""
find the row data

put into dictonary and zip into the list

create 2020 lanuch dataframe 

"""
import pandas as pd

#find row data 
row_data = My_table.select('tr:not(:has(td[colspan="9"]))')
data_dict = []

#loop the row and search the row with th and th 
for row in row_data[1:-1]:
    row_ls = []
    
    cells = row.findAll(['th','td'])
    
    for cell in cells:
        row_ls.append(cell.get_text(strip = True))
            

    data_dict.append(dict(zip(column_names, row_ls)))
    
df = pd.DataFrame(data_dict,columns = column_names)
